node.text:
Farmers need five things to succeed: good land, good seeds, farming supplies, time, and know-how.

Patricia, a farmer I met in Malawi, had barriers standing between her and every one of those things simply because she was a woman. But she overcame them. I wrote about her story in The #MomentofLift.

node.text:
Since COVID-19 emerged, I’ve been thinking about women I’ve met on my travels and how they’re doing. Can Patricia, a farmer in Malawi, still sell her crops when fewer people are gathering at the market? Does Christina, a teacher in Kentucky, have the tools to shift to remote learning? 

The pandemic has made the barriers these women face even more daunting. But it’s also an opportunity to build the better future they deserve.

Click the link in my bio to read our 2021 Annual Letter. m-gat.es/2KTNqE4

node.title: How to Make Sure Women are Not Left Behind Post-COVID

node.text:
2020 was the year global health went local.

COVID-19 brought home the fact that all of humanity is connected and diseases don’t care about borders.

The good news is: If we make sure the pandemic response reaches everyone, everywhere, we can create a world that’s healthier, more equal, and more resilient. 

Read more in this year’s Annual Letter. https://m-gat.es/2KTNqE4 

Link in my bio to learn more.

node.title: How We’ll Build a More Equal Post-COVID Future

node.text:
In 2014, my daughter Jenn and I stayed with a woman named Anna and her family in Tanzania. Anna told us about the small but courageous act that changed her life, her family, and her community.

Her story has stuck with me ever since. I wrote The #MomentofLift to share stories like Anna’s. I hope they inspire you like they’ve inspired me.

node.title: How Anna Summoned a Moment of Lift

node.text:
My parents taught me to leave the world better than I found it.

I know so many people across this country believe in giving back, too. Throughout the pandemic, Americans have shown up for each other in extraordinary ways.
 
In a year like no other, let’s make this a giving season like no other—starting with #GivingTuesday.

A great way to get involved is by using our foundation’s dedicated website, PowerOf.org, to find nonprofits in your community to support.
 
We all have the power to make a difference in someone’s life, and we can begin today.

Following public health guidance can help stop the spread of #COVID19, which is why I’m answering @who’s call to join the #SafeHands Challenge.⁣ ⁣

It also gives me a chance to share three things that are on my mind as we all go through this difficult time.⁣
⁣
1. We need to listen to science and public health experts. Social distancing and washing our hands are our best tools right now to prevent the spread of the virus and ease the strain on our health system.⁣
⁣
2. So many people are suffering because of this pandemic, so let’s support each other and support the most vulnerable in our communities.⁣
⁣
3. Have compassion for yourself and others. Find ways to take care of yourself, and be sure to check in on your friends and family.⁣

node.text: When women are empowered to time and space their pregnancies, the impacts ripple through communities. That's why the @gatesfoundation is expanding our commitment to family planning over the next five years. Women and girls across the world are telling us they want and need contraceptives to lead healthier and more productive lives. We should listen.

node.text:
Here’s the message I shared at last week's #GenerationEquality Forum—the largest gathering in 26 years of people working for gender equality:

It is precisely when we confront how broken things are that we have the most power to reimagine them and lay a foundation for a more resilient society. Finally, we can center women and girls in all their diversity instead of marginalizing them.

Part of the role of philanthropy is to support us in our fight. In that spirit, I am announcing that the Gates Foundation will invest $2.1 billion in women’s empowerment over the next five years.

We think about this work in terms of three priorities: cash, care, and data. Cash means making sure that recovery, stimulus, and social protection money gets directly into women’s hands.

Care means helping countries build a sustainable caregiving infrastructure instead of just relying on women to do it all, unpaid.

And data means making the invisible visible so that we can pinpoint the needs of women and girls, develop evidence-based policies, and monitor progress.

Our foundation has been committed to family planning and women’s health since we started. We are reaffirming that commitment with $1.4 billion through 2026 to support our partners in developing new and improved contraceptive technologies and meeting women and girls’ needs for accessible, high quality care. We know that when women control their bodies and their futures, they unlock a cycle of empowerment that reverberates for generations.

Finally, with an initial commitment of $100 million through 2026, we will support women’s leadership in the fields of health, economics, and law. Women are still systematically locked out of positions of power. The only way we can deliver an equal world is to be in the rooms where pivotal decisions get made.

The beauty of our fight for gender equality is that every human being will gain from it. We are not playing a zero-sum game where one group’s success is another’s failure. In our world, when you are encouraged and supported to become whoever you want to be, the horizon expands. In our world, equal is greater. Let’s build that more equal world together.

It matters for everyone that we lift the barriers women face around the world. Because when a society is more equal, it's also more prosperous.

I believe we are in a rare window of opportunity to rapidly accelerate progress for gender equality, and I'm proud to say the @gatesfoundation is committing $2.1 billion to help deliver change.

Let's seize this moment to build a better, more equitable future. 

#GenerationEquality #ActForEqual
